Triple negative breast cancer (TNBC) originates from a less differentiated ductal cell of breast, which is less sensitive to chemotherapy. The chemotolerance mechanism of TNBC has not yet been studied in detail. For this reason, molecular profiles (expression/genetic/epigenetic) of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin (active) and its kinase epider- mal growth factor receptor (EGFR) along with SH3GL2 (regulator of EGFR

homeostasis) were compared between neoadjuvant chemotherapy treated (NACT) and pretherapeutic TNBC samples. Reduced nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin protein with low proliferation index and CD44 prevalence showed concordance with reduced expression of EGFR/Y1045‐p‐EGFR proteins in the NACT samples than the pretherapeutic TNBC samples. Infrequent messenger RNA expression, gene amplification (10–32.5%), and mutation (1%) of EGFR were seen in the TNBC samples irrespective of therapy, suggesting the importance of EGFR protein stabilization in this tumor. The upregulation of SH3GL2 seen in the NACT samples hypomethylation, as seen in the quantitative methylation assay. A similar trend of upregulation of SH3GL2 and downregulation of EGFR, Y1045‐p‐EGFR, Y654‐p‐β‐ catenin were seen in the MDA‐MB‐231 cell line using antharacycline antitumor drugs (doxorubicin/nogalamycin). The NACT patients with reduced expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin and/or EGFR and high expression of SH3GL2 showed compara- tively better prognosis than the pretherapeutic patients. Thus, our study showed that reduced nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin in NACT samples due to downregulation of EGFR protein through promoter hypomethylation‐mediated upregulation of SH3GL2, resulting in low proliferation index/CD44 prevalence with better prognosis of the NACT patients, might have an important role in the neoadjuvant chemotherapy treated, pretherapeutic, promoter hypomethylation, triple negative breast cancer, Y654‐p‐β‐catenin wileyonlinelibrary.com/journal/jcp to the pretherapeutic samples might be due to its promoter © 2020 Wiley Periodicals, Inc. Triple negative breast cancer (TNBC), the most aggressive subtype of breast cancer is defined as a reduced expression of estrogen receptor

(ER), progesterone receptor (PR), and HER2, which is epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (EGFR2; Foulkes, Smith, & Reis‐Filho, 2010). World- wide, its prevalence is 10–15%, while in the Indian subcontinent, its prevalence is approximately 25–31% (Plasilova et al., 2016; Sandhu, Erqou, Patterson, & Mathew, 2016; Thakur, Bordoloi, & Kunnumakkara, 2017). It is resistant to radiotherapy, hormonal therapy, and anti‐Her2 therapy (Langlands, Horgan, Dodwell, & Smith, 2013; Wahba & El‐ Hadaad, 2015). Initially, it was sensitive to neoadjuvant chemotherapy (NAC), and its prognosis (28–36%) was found to be better than pretherapeutic patients (22%; Liedtke et al., 2008; Omarini et al., 2018). However, its loco‐regional recurrence rate is very high within a short time span (Munzone & Colleoni, 2017; Yao et al., 2017). NAC consists of a set of an anthracycline group of drugs (doxorubicin/ epirubicin) along with 5‐flurouracile and cyclophosphamide given to patients before surgery for increasing the feasibility of surgery through reduction in tumor size (Munzone & Colleoni, 2017). The residual tumor cells after neoadjuvant chemotherapy treated (NACT) could be defined as chemotolerant cells having a low proliferation index (Balko et al., 2014; Dasgupta et al., 2017). It has been suggested that these cells are dormant with a less differentiated stem cell like character unlike untreated cancer stem cells (Sharma et al., 2010). As a result, these cells are mainly involved in the recurrence of disease with limited treatment options (Basile & Aplin, 2012). Thus, it is necessary to understand the molecular profile of NACT TNBC cells for better therapeutics.

Frequent alterations of the WNT stem cell renewal pathway with the activation of β‐catenin have been seen in primary TNBC (Mukherjee et al., 2016; Pohl et al., 2017). The activation of β‐catenin occurs through its cytoplasmic stabilization followed by nuclear localization by cascade of phosphorylations at the C‐terminal end (Lu, Ghosh, Wang, & Hunter, 2003; Nakayama et al., 2014). Among the phosphorylations sites, high Y654 phosphorylation by EGFR has been seen in primary TNBC (Mukherjee et al., 2016; van Veelen et al., 2011). Differential overexpression (37–90%) of EGFR protein with infrequent amplification(4.1–33%), mutation (0–11.4%), and mRNA overexpression (0–25%) were seen in pretherapeutic TNBC samples (Kim, Jang, Lee, & Bae, 2017; Meseure et al., 2012; Secq et al., 2014; Sobande et al., 2015). It seems that overexpression of EGFR protein in TNBC might be due to its increased stability through alterations of the homeostasis mechanism as seen in other tumors (Madshus & Stang, 2009; Maiti et al., 2013). The homeostasis of EGFR is controlled by clathrin‐dependent endocytosis through its phosphor- ylation at Tyr‐1045 followed by interaction with the Cbl‐CIN85‐ SH3GL2 network (Foley et al., 2012; Leemans, Braakhuis, & Brake- nhoff, 2011). Inactivation of SH3GL2 by deletion/methylation has been reported in BC (Sinha et al., 2008). But, the association of SH3GL2 with the expression of EGFR and Y654‐p‐β‐catenin in the chemotolerance of TNBC has not yet been studied in detail. Thus, attempts have been made in this study to analyze the protein expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin and its association with

proliferation in pretherapeutic (N = 67) and NACT (N = 17) TNBC samples at first, followed by its correlation with molecular profiles (expression/copy number variation/mutation/methylation) of EGFR and SH3GL2 in the same set of samples. Our study showed the association of reduced nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin and low proliferation index in NACT TNBC. This might be due to the downregulation of EGFR/Y1045‐p‐EGFR proteins and upregulation of SH3GL2 by frequent promoter hypomethylation as seen in our 2 | M A T E R I A L S AN D M E T H O D S A total of 67 pretherapeutic (without any chemotherapy/radio- therapy treatment) and 17 unrelated NACT primary invasive breast tumors after molecular subtyping analysis (i.e., immunohistochem- istry of ER, PR, and HER2 receptors), adjacent normal tissues along with 5 ml blood of the corresponding patients were collected from the hospital section of Chittaranjan National Cancer Institute (CNCI), Kolkata during 1999–2015. On the other hand, patients (a) suffering from severe viral diseases (like HBV/HIV) or (b) received radio- therapy before surgery were excluded from the study. All the TNBC samples were classified into different stage and grade according to the Union for International Cancer Control and tumor node metastasis (TNM) classification. The scoring of loss of heterozygosity (LOH), micro- satellite size alterations of one allele (MAI), microsatellite size alterations of two alleles (MAII), biallelic alterations like LMA (LOH + MA) was done in autoradiograms, according to a previous standard protocol (Dasgupta et al., 2002). 2.10 | Effect of 5‐aza‐DC on methylation of SH3GL2 in MDA‐MB‐231 TNBC cell lines To understand the effect of promoter methylation on the expression of SH3GL2, the demethylation experiment was per- formed in the MDA‐MB‐231 cell line using demethylating agent 5‐ Aza‐2′‐deoxycytidine (5‐aza‐dC) according to our previous method (Mukherjee et al., 2016). The 10 and 20 μM doses of 5‐aza‐dC were selected based on our previous cell viability assay (Mukher- jee et al., 2016). Subconfluent cultures of these two cell lines were exposed to a desired concentration of 5‐aza‐dC for 5 days without changing media, as cell viability was unaltered during this time (Maiti et al., 2013). Controls without 5‐aza‐dC were cultured parallelly in the same method. After treatment, cells were collected and used for RNA isolation as well as real quantification of the genes (SH3GL2, EGFR) using SYBR green as mentioned in the mRNA expression analysis section. A comparatively low frequency of mRNA expression of EGFR was seen in the NACT samples (mean fold change 0.59‐fold) than pretherapeutic samples (mean fold change 0.87‐fold; Figure 2j), though there was no concordance between mRNA and protein expression of EGFR irrespective of therapy (Figure 2j; Tables S3 and S4). in NACT samples, genetic alterations (amplification/mutation) of the EGFR were analyzed. Infrequent amplification of EGFR was seen in NACT (7.6%, 3/17) and pre‐therapeutic (13.4%, 9/67) samples (Figure 2k, m). The amplification of the gene was validated by qRT‐ PCR analysis using SYBR green (p = .001; Figure 2l). In mutation screening of kinase domain of EGFR (exon‐18 to 21), an infrequent abnormal band shift (1/41) was seen in exon‐20 of the pretherapeutic samples with changes in synonymous G > A transition at the 787th codon (Figure 2n,o). However, no concordance was seen between amplification/mutation and protein expression of EGFR, irrespective of therapy (Tables S3 and S4). Thus, the reduced expression of EGFR and Y1045‐p‐EGFR proteins in the NACT samples might be due to the modulation of the EGFR homeostasis mechanism. 3.2 | Upregulation of SH3GL2 in NACT TNBC samples To understand the EGFR homeostasis mechanism in NACT samples, alterations (deletion/methylation/expression) of SH3GL2 (endocyto- sis regulator of EGFR) were analyzed in the NACT and prether- expression of SH3GL2 protein was observed in both luminal

epithelial and myoepithelium cells of normal breast duct (Figure 3a,b). In the pre‐therapeutic samples, the SH3GL2 expression was highly reduced (63.6%, 28/44) than the NACT samples (52.9%, 9/17) (Figure 3c–e). Like protein expression, the mRNA expression of SH3GL2 was highly reduced in the pretherapeutic samples (average fold reduction −3.6) than the NACT (average fold reduction −1.34) samples (Figure 3f). In pre‐therapeutic samples, a reduced expression of SH3GL2 was significantly associated with the overexpression of EGFR (p = .0019), Y1045‐p‐EGFR (p = .0005), and nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin (p = .046; Table 3). However, no such correlation was seen in the NACT samples, probably due to the increased expression of SH3GL2 protein (Table 3). EGFR, epidermal growth factor receptor; NACT, neoadjuvant chemotherapy treatment; TNBC, triple negative breast cancer In our study, there is no significant difference in survival between the pretherapeutic and NACT TNBC samples followed by validation in a line MDA‐MB‐231. Comparatively reduced expression of TNBC cell nuclear Y654‐p‐β‐catenin in the NACT samples (29.5%) than the pretherapeutic samples (43.2%) indicate its importance in the chemoto- lerance of TNBC. To the best of our knowledge, no such study has been

done in NACT TNBC samples. Unlike pretherapeutic samples, the reduced expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin showed concordance with low proliferation index and CD44+ stem cell prevalence in NACT samples. It seems that Y654‐p‐β‐catenin is involved in dormancy of chemotolerant TNBC through modulation of cell proliferation and EMT (Bartosh, Ullah, Zeitouni, Beaver, & Prockop, 2016; Olmeda, Castel, Vilaro, & Cano, 2003; Pradhan, Sperduto, Farino, & Slater, 2018). In contrast to pretherapeutic samples, reduced nuclear expres- sion of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin showed concordance with reduced expres- sion of EGFR and Y1045‐p‐EGFR proteins in the NACT samples. Thus, it indicates that low nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin might be due to the low expression of its kinase EGFR (Daugherty & Gottardi, 2007; Lu et al., 2003). However, no such change in EGFR protein expression was reported in NACT colorectal cancer and non‐ small cell lung cancer (Khalifa et al., 2006; Shanlin Xu, Jing, Jia, Jujie, & Dianbin, 2013). This difference might be due to tissue types and use of methods. In our study, the discordance of EGFR protein expression with mRNA expression and copy number variation irrespective of therapy suggests the EGFR protein expression might be due to its stabilization. A similar phenomenon has also been reported in breast cancer (BC; Grimminger et al., 2011). However, Singh et al. (2012) showed high expression mRNA and protein of EGFR in BC2. This discrepancy might be due to sample size, ethnicity, etiological factors, and use of different methods of analysis. It was evident that EGFR protein stability is negatively regulated by SH3GL2 through modulation of homeostasis mechanism. Thus, reduced expression of EGFR protein in the NACT samples might be due to increase expression (mRNA/protein) of SH3GL2 contrary to

the pretherapeutic samples, as seen in our study. than the deletion has been seen in the samples irrespective of therapy, suggesting importance of the promoter methylation in this tumor. A similar phenomenon has also been reported in BC (Singh et al., 2012). However, upregulation of SH3GL2 seen in the NACT samples than the pretherapeutic sample might be due to its promoter hypomethylation as seen in quantitative methylation assay. Likewise, hypomethylation of genes BRCA1, BRCA2, FNACC, MLH1, and MLH2 has also been was reported in NACT TNBC samples and suggested to be due to downregulation of DNMT1 (Dasgupta et al., 2017, 2018). Thus, upregulation of SH3GL2 in the cell line after treatment of the drugs could downregulate the EGFR receptor followed by Y654‐p‐β‐ catenin, resulting in low proliferation of the cell. It seems that unlike pretherapeutic patients concordance between (a) reduced nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin with late stage (III/IV) of TNBC and (b) increased expression of SH3GL2 and reduced expression of EGFR and Y1045‐p‐EGFR (p = .0038) with high grade of tumor in the NACT samples might lead to better a clinical outcome of the patients. In addition, comparatively better prognosis of NACT patients with (a) reduced expression of Y654‐p‐β‐ catenin and/or EGFR and (b) high expression of SH3GL2 and low

expression of EGFR than the pretherapeutic patients with significant poor survival suggests their prognostic importance. Thus, our data suggest that reduced nuclear expression of Y654‐p‐β‐catenin in NACT samples due to reduced expression of EGFR by SH3GL2 upregulation through promoter hypomethylation resulting in low proliferation index/CD44 prevalence with better prognosis of the NACT patients might have an important role in chemotolerance of TNBC (Figure 6).
